John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scottish private schools maintain a track record of academic excellence, and this was continued in 2018 with outstanding test results, further reinforced by each student and collective success in sport, art, music as well as hard work.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Private School Board (SCIS) strive to provide the best service for students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for advanced and higher education, their chosen careers, and their role as world citizens.
As the education sector can design and implement the school curriculum as expected, we see modern language continues to be a popular and desirable subject of choice in many schools.
Nelson Mandela said: "If you talk to someone in a language he understands, your speech will go into his head.
If you talk to him in his language then your words will go into his heart."
This is a strong reminder that we can’t just rely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of the most recent exam this year, we can see that the language is the top of the league table with the highest graduation score in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who learn a foreign language get an A Plus grade.
The data, collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students got an A Plus grade in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who learned German, 69 percent of those who learned French and 63 percent who learned Spanish also got an A grade.
This suggests that independent schools in Scotland support foreign language as an important skill that will certainly be required by children and adolescents in the future.
Today the languages, as a choice of subjects, are held in the same standard as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in modern school curriculums and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK’s Employment and Skills Service in 2014 found that out of several reasons why employers should continue to struggle to fill vacancies, 17 percent of the reason is a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly encouraged to prepare teenagers for their future careers.
With an increasing number of job opportunities requiring language skills, these skills are important in a globalized world.
Whatever one’s career choice, if they have already learned a second language, in the future they will feel the real benefit of having this kind of lifelong skill.
Being able to communicate directly with residents of a foreign country will automatically make a multilingual superior in the competition.
According to a YouGov poll of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent of them did not speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation and French became the only language spoken in double-digit percentages, which is 15 percent.
This is why investing in language teaching for today’s children is an important thing for today.
Having multilingual skills, especially the languages of countries with a growing economy, will equip children with better opportunities to find meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, each school will teach a different language.
Some schools will focus on a more classical modern language, while others will teach the language that is considered the most important in the UK for the next few years, namely 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools, with an expert teaching staff in this field.
The Scottish independent school is intended to provide a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills necessary to succeed, no matter what happens in the future.
It cannot be denied that nowadays, in a global business environment, language will always be an important aspect in determining the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be considered as "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity, and excellence for Scottish youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Board of Independent Schools
