Harvard students take courses on adequate rest
A new course at Harvard University this year puts all of the undergraduate students there to sleep more, in an effort against the macho culture in learning that is developing through a caffeine-powered 'orange man'.
An academic found that students at the world’s number one university often don’t know anything about discussing a very basic thing about how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of medicine specializing in sleep problems at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
He was inspired to start the course after giving lectures on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At last a girl came up to me and said: ‘Why am I just being told now, in my final year?’
The girl said no one had ever told me about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
The course, launched for the first time this year, explains to students the essence of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic outcomes, as well as improve their general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce this course after finding students who were severely deprived of sleep throughout the week.
This one-hour course involves a series of interactive tasks.
In one session there was a picture of a dormitory room, where students clicked on coffee cups, curtains, sports pants, and books to get an explanation of the effects of caffeine and lamps, as well as how athletic results were affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of sleep time routines.
In other sections, participants got an explanation as to how long sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
'We know this won't change students' behavior instantly.
But we believe that they have a right to know — just as you have a right to know the effect of choosing to smoke cigarettes on health,” Prof Czeisler said.
The culture of pride in ‘begging’ still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students which means sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Making sure you sleep enough, with good quality, should be a ‘secret weapon’ to fight stress, fatigue, and anxiety, he said – even to avoid weight gain, because lack of sleep makes the brain activate hunger mode, creating a constant sense of hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California resident who studied chemistry and physical biology who helped Professor Czeisler design the course, had taken one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said that this course had opened his eyes and inspired him to organize the course for the entire campus.
The next step, she hopes that all graduate students are instructed to complete a similar course of study before joining a competitive institution.
Prof Czeisler recommends that students should consider setting sleep time alarms, also wake alarms, and be aware of the effects of ‘blue light' emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can shift your circadian rhythm out of its set path causing sleep problems.
